&lt;hr>
&lt;h1 id="integrating-force-graph-3d-into-a-nextjs-project-a-simple-demo">Integrating &lt;code>force-graph-3d&lt;/code> into a Next.js Project: A Simple Demo
&lt;/h1>&lt;p>If you&amp;rsquo;re exploring ways to visualize knowledge graphs or network data in 3D using React and Next.js, you&amp;rsquo;ve probably come across the popular library &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/vasturiano/force-graph" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>&lt;strong>&lt;code>force-graph&lt;/code>&lt;/strong>&lt;/a> by &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/vasturiano" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>@vasturiano&lt;/a>. In this post, I’ll walk through how I integrated &lt;strong>&lt;code>force-graph-3d&lt;/code>&lt;/strong> — its WebGL-based 3D force-directed graph implementation — into a &lt;strong>Next.js&lt;/strong> app as part of my ongoing &lt;strong>Knowledge Graph + LLM&lt;/strong> project.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>You can check out the full code here:&lt;br>
👉 &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/gwzz/Knowledge_Graph_X_LLM/tree/main/visulization/graph-visualization" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>GitHub - Knowledge_Graph_X_LLM / graph-visualization&lt;/a>&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>⚠️ Note: This is more of a proof-of-concept/demo than a production-ready solution. There’s still work to be done before this can scale to large or complex graphs, but it’s a solid starting point!&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;hr>
&lt;h2 id="-why-use-force-graph-3d">🎯 Why Use &lt;code>force-graph-3d&lt;/code>?
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>&lt;code>force-graph-3d&lt;/code> offers an interactive and performant way to render large-scale 3D graphs directly in the browser using WebGL. It supports:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Dynamic force simulation&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Custom node/camera controls&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Real-time updates&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Click/touch interactions&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>Since I&amp;rsquo;m working on visualizing knowledge graphs generated via LLMs, having a 3D layout helps users better understand relationships and hierarchies in a visually rich format.&lt;/p>
&lt;hr>
&lt;h2 id="-setting-up-the-nextjs-environment">🛠️ Setting Up the Next.js Environment
&lt;/h2>&lt;p>I started with a basic &lt;code>create-next-app&lt;/code> setup:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">npx create-next-app@latest graph-visualization
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Then installed the required dependencies:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div class="chroma">
&lt;table class="lntable">&lt;tr>&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code>&lt;span class="lnt">1
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td class="lntd">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">npm install three force-graph-3d
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>💡 &lt;code>force-graph-3d&lt;/code> relies on &lt;strong>Three.js&lt;/strong>, so make sure it&amp;rsquo;s included (either directly or as a peer dependency).&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;hr>
